With a September 2025 release date, Jessica Chastain’s _The Savant_ had been set to release just two weeks before Apple pulled it from its programming in part to the Utah Valley assassination of Charlie Kirk on September 10th of last year.

“I can say we’re going to see it,” Chastain noted while speaking to Variety at the Breakthrough Prize Ceremony on Saturday night in Santa Monica. Interviewer Marc Malkin noted that his sources say the show will air in July.

The Savant, shot in April of 2024, follows a 2019 story out of COSMOPOLITAN maganize about a woman that uses the internet to detect hate crimes before they happen. The woman, portrayed by Academy Award winner Jessica Chastain, uses online techniques to detect potential hates crimes before they happen. Chastain is notable for extensive dramatic excellence in film, in both blockbusters such as _Interstellar_ and _It: Chapter 2,_ as well as independent auteur-driven vehicles such as _The Tree of Life, Take Shelter,_ and _Molly’s Game._ A three-time Academy Award winner, Chastain had been nominated in Best Supporting Actress for _The Help_ and Best Lead Actress for _Zero Dark Thirty_ until her win for 2021’s _The Eyes of Tammy Faye_, where she portrayed controversial televangelist Tammy Faye Bakker. More recently, her showtime miniseries _Tammy and George_ opposite Michael Shannon as a biopic about country legends George Jones and Tammy Wynette garnered her third Screen Actors Guild Award and first PrimeTime Emmy nomination.

Chastain’s support in the series consists of former Oakland Raiders All-Pro cornerback Nnamdi Asomugha. Asomugha, who has been acting in feature films since he was a member of the Philadelphia Eagles active roster, has worked with AppleTV+ previously as a producer on _The Banker._ The show also features a regular role from Pablo Schreiber, most fondly remembered for his turn as Pornstache Mendez in _Orange is the New Black,_ the show that made Netflix a major player in the television medium. Schreiber’s other television work includes _Halo_ and Tessa Thompson’s _His and Hers_.

The series and its concept drew ire from one side of the political aisle because it reportedly is a scathing indictment on the growing risk of white supremacy in the United States, while also garnering criticism from the other side of the aisle for covering a division within the ADL, which is a Pro-Israel organization that’s been working within the United States since the Wilson administration. Eight days after the postponement of the series, then-FBI Director Kash Patel controversially ended a partnership that the federal government had with the ADL division that the series is based upon. White supremacy currently represents a vast majority of terrostic threats domestically in the United States amidst a tumultuous political climate, and the show doesn’t seem to shy away from that, probably being the cause of the delay during an even more tumultuous political climate. To say that this series was already politically charged before an incident regarding a polarizing political pundit would be an understatement. “I’ve never shied away from difficult subjects,” Chastain posted on her social medias following the delayment, “and while I wish this show wasn’t so relevant, it unfortunately is.” Chastain continued to make it clear she did not appreciate the decision.

However, many have pondered whether or not Apple’s decision to delay the show brought more eyes to it than it would have had it otherwise dropped business as usual.

